newsitem.title: USA: CBOT Dec wheat ends up on fund buying, Mar set low.
newsitem.headline: CBOT Dec wheat ends up on fund buying, Mar set low.

text.p: CBOT wheat futures closed mixed with nearby December higher on fund buying, traders said.
March ended higher but a new low was set early in that contract at $3.65-1/2 per bushel, down from the previous low of $3.67 set Thursday.
LIT America bought three million bushels of December, Rosenthal Collins bought 1.5 million December and Lehman Brothers bought 1.5 million December, traders said.
Traders said the late recovery in the nearbys was tied to signals the market was technically oversold and due for a bounce.
The short term nine day relative strength index (RSI) for December closed at 24.3 points, well below the 30 level which is an area generally considered an oversold mark.
Traders said the stiff competition worldwide for wheat export business and renewed concern about the karnal bunt fungus continued to limit market rallies.
There was news Thursday that karnal bunt had been found in some Tennessee wheat which triggered concerns the fungus might surface in other soft red winter wheat areas.
Wheat closed 3-1/2 cents a bushel higher to 4-3/4 lower, with December up 3-1/2 at $3.74-3/4.
"Karnal bunt didn't help wheat any," said Vic Lespinasse of Dean Witter Reynolds.
Declines in soybeans also continued to limit attempts to rally the wheat market.
Wheat futures volume was estimated at 13,000 contracts, down from 19,782 Thursday, according to the CBOT.
In wheat options FIMAT Futures bought 1,000 March $4.30 calls at 1-1/2 cents, traders said.
Wheat options volume was estimated at 5,000 contracts, down from 7,089 Thursday.
